\begin_layout Standard
Why has mating-type switching repeatedly evolved? The most significant verbal
 hypothesis on the adaptive advantage of mating-type switching is the so-called
 ``lonely spore hypothesis'' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Knop2006,Lin2007a,Hanson2014"

\end_inset

.
 This hypothesis considers a life cycle of ascomycete yeasts, in which a
 diploid parent (always heterozygous for mating type alleles 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha/a$
\end_inset

) produces four haploid spores, half of which bears allele 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 while the other half bears allele 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 When this ascus survives intact, the resulting colony is able to have sexual
 reproduction and hence sporulation; yet in the likely event that the ascus
 breaks and a colony is founded from a single spore, only clonal reproduction
 (and hence no sporulation) would be possible.
 Here, mating type switching is thought to be selectively advantageous,
 as it allows offspring cells to change their mating type, thus providing
 a partner to the parental cell 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Knop2006,Lin2007a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scenario above is a rather extreme example of a more general phenomenon,
 where drift due to small effective population sizes causes distortions
 in the distribution of mating types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fisher1930,Iwasa1987"

\end_inset

.
 The evolution of mating type switching could then be selectively advantageous,
 as it increases the production of rare mating type alleles (which have
 a higher reproductive value), ultimately resulting in a more even distribution
 of mating type alleles.
 However, when and where mating type switching will evolve in response to
 drift (and what switching rate will evolve) has yet to be systematically
 analyzed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notable in this context is a recent study by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Paixao2011"

\end_inset

, who modeled the evolution of stochastic mating type determination following
 sex and recombination.
 This study shows that species with multiple mating types would benefit
 from randomizing the mating type of offspring following sex, so that the
 mating type of the offspring is randomized.
 Such a mechanism counters a distortion in the sex ratio and can explain
 sex determination mechanisms such as those seen in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Tetrahymena}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Other ciliates and fungi, however, exhibit a different mechanism of mating-type
 switching that involves fewer mating type loci (typically two), in which
 offspring mating types are not randomly determined, but often (but not
 always) attain the mating type opposite to that of the parental cell 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Li2012"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, life cycles of most fungi and protists are characterized by
 a substantial number of clonal cell divisions before sexual reproduction
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ni2011,Speijer2015"

\end_inset

, so that stochasticity in clonal cell replication could lead to increased
 genetic drift acting on the distribution of mating type alleles.
 To what extent asexual reproduction modulates the evolution of mating type
 switching is currently poorly understood.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the current study, we therefore systematically assess when and where
 mating type switching is important in countering fluctuations in finite
 populations.
 To this end, we develop a finite population model to study the evolution
 of alleles imposing stochastic mating type switching during clonal growth.
 By explicitly modeling both the asexual and sexual phases of protists'
 life cycles, we examine the conditions under which switching evolves.
 Specifically the role of the population size, duration of asexual reproduction,
 switching rates and other possible sources of stochasticity that may distort
 the sex ratio.
 This allows us to make predictions about when switching should evolve and
 what the expected switching rates would be in real populations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To capture the effect of drift due to a finite population size and clonal
 replication on the simultaneous evolution of mating type alleles and mating
 type switching, we use individual-based simulations of a population of
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 haploid cells, in which each cell bears two genetically encoded loci.
 The first locus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 codes for an individual's mating type and contains alleles 
\begin_inset Formula $\{M_{1},M_{2},M_{3},…,M_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a parameter specifying the maximum possible number of different mating
 types.
 An individual bearing allele 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}$
\end_inset

 cannot mate with other individuals bearing the same allele.
 In addition, we also consider a mating type switching locus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, which contains one wildtype allele 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and a mutant allele 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, which changes the inheritance of the mating type allele at the locus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 (see below).
 We assume that linkage between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 is absent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a life cycle in which cells undergo 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 rounds of clonal growth, before engaging in sexual reproduction.
 During each round of vegetative growth, each cell produces a daughter cell,
 changing the population size from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2N.$
\end_inset

 We assume that the carrying capacity of the population is fixed and sample
 without replacement to return to a population size equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 At each vegetative generation we assume that daugdaughter cell inherits
 its parent's genotype for the switching locus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 Inheritance at locus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 depends on the alleles present at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

: if the wildtype allele 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is present, the daughter always inherits the maternal mating type allele.
 By contrast, when 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is present, the daughter cell in herits the maternal mating type allele
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p_{s}$
\end_inset

, whereas it inherits a randomly chosen and different allele with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Following the clonal growth stage, cells mate with one another at random,
 where only cells that are heterotypic at the mating type locus can mate.
 To give an example of the dynamics during mating, consider a case in which
 a population contains only two mating type loci, with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 individuals bearing allele 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}=N-N_{1}$
\end_inset

 individuals bear allele 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In case allele 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 is rarer than 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}<N_{2}$
\end_inset

), we then end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 randomly chosen pairs of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}\times M_{2}$
\end_inset

 individuals, while the remainder of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}-N_{1}$
\end_inset

 individuals bearing the more common allele 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 are unable to reproduce.
 After mating, mated (diploid) individuals then undergo meiosis to give
 rise to the next generation.
 If the number of mated pairs is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $N/2$
\end_inset

, the population is allowed to grow back to carrying capacity.
 No switching occurs at the meiotic step.
 This life cycle encompasses alternating clonal and sexual phases, universal
 amongst protists.
 We also consider several extensions to this simplest framework.
 The life cycle is illustrated schematically on Fig.1, and our model parameters
 are summarized on Table 
